ue":"\n"},{"type":"element","tagName":"li","properties":{},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"vmax - height or width, whichever is larger","position":{"start":{"line":18,"column":5,"offset":970},"end":{"line":18,"column":48,"offset":1013}}}],"position":{"start":{"line":18,"column":1,"offset":966},"end":{"line":18,"column":48,"offset":1013}}},{"type":"text","value":"\n"}],"position":{"start":{"line":15,"column":1,"offset":865},"end":{"line":18,"column":48,"offset":1013}}},{"type":"text","value":"\n"},{"type":"element","tagName":"p","properties":{},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"So the reason viewport units are not used more extensively is probably not due to a lack of browser support or developers' understanding. My guess is it’s probably more likely to do with the lack of precise control designers have over the font-size.","position":{"start":{"line":20,"column":1,"offset":1015},"end":{"line":20,"column":250,"offset":1264}}}],"position":{"start":{"line":20,"column":1,"offset":1015},"end":{"line":20,"column":250,"offset":1264}}},{"type":"text","value":"\n"},{"type":"element","tagName":"p","properties":{},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"Designers that love typography often really love typography and they enjoy precise control over line-height, font-size, letter-spacing and other elements of typography those of us not in the club might not even know exist.","position":{"start":{"line":22,"column":1,"offset":1266},"end":{"line":22,"column":223,"offset":1488}}}],"position":{"start":{"line":22,"column":1,"offset":1266},"end":{"line":22,"column":223,"offset":1488}}},{"type":"text","value":"\n"},{"type":"element","tagName":"p","properties":{},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"This desire for precise control is the reason that some designers still prefer to declare these properties using pixels. But it doesn’t really matter, whether they use ems, rems or percentages the truth is, they are all just abstractions of a base font size and that is usually 16 pixels. So they have never really had to give up complete control. It’s not difficult to work out what font-size an element is, as long as we know the base font-size.","position":{"start":{"line":24,"column":1,"offset":1490},"end":{"line":24,"column":448,"offset":1937}}}],"position":{"start":{"line":24,"column":1,"offset":1490},"end":{"line":24,"column":448,"offset":1937}}},{"type":"text","value":"\n"},{"type":"element","tagName":"p","properties":{},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"But viewport units are different! They represent a fundamental change in approach. Unlike all the other units, viewport units are not relative to the base font size in any way. Instead they are relative to the viewport, which the user controls, and that might be scary for some.","position":{"start":{"line":26,"column":1,"offset":1939},"end":{"line":26,"column":279,"offset":2217}}}],"position":{"start":{"line":26,"column":1,"offset":1939},"end":{"line":26,"column":279,"offset":2217}}},{"type":"text","value":"\n"},{"type":"element","tagName":"p","properties":{},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"But there are advantages to using viewport units, a font-size declared with viewport units is fluid, meaning it will scale smoothly. This is a clearly a better experience than ","position":{"start":{"line":28,"column":1,"offset":2219},"end":{"line":28,"column":177,"offset":2395}}},{"type":"element","tagName":"a","properties":{"href":"http://codepen.io/MadeByMike/pen/c54dfa521cf08e0439943b7a745f77f0"},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"clunky responsive typography techniques","position":{"start":{"line":28,"column":178,"offset":2396},"end":{"line":28,"column":217,"offset":2435}}}],"position":{"start":{"line":28,"column":177,"offset":2395},"end":{"line":28,"column":285,"offset":2503}}},{"type":"text","value":" that require multiple media queries.","position":{"start":{"line":28,"column":285,"offset":2503},"end":{"line":28,"column":322,"offset":2540}}}],"position":{"start":{"line":28,"column":1,"offset":2219},"end":{"line":28,"column":322,"offset":2540}}},{"type":"text","value":"\n"},{"type":"element","tagName":"p","properties":{},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"Responsive typography with viewport units is really easy to implement, just declare the base font-size using vw; as long as you are not using pixels elsewhere in your stylesheet, other units are relative to the base font-size, (which is now viewport units) so they will all scale accordingly.","position":{"start":{"line":30,"column":1,"offset":2542},"end":{"line":30,"column":293,"offset":2834}}}],"position":{"start":{"line":30,"column":1,"offset":2542},"end":{"line":30,"column":293,"offset":2834}}},{"type":"text","value":"\n"},{"type":"element","tagName":"p","properties":{},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"But there are a few rough edges you will need to sand back. Firstly when you get down to a very small viewport scaling is problematic. Luckily there are a few good methods for avoiding this.","position":{"start":{"line":32,"column":1,"offset":2836},"end":{"line":32,"column":191,"offset":3026}}}],"position":{"start":{"line":32,"column":1,"offset":2836},"end":{"line":32,"column":191,"offset":3026}}},{"type":"text","value":"\n"},{"type":"element","tagName":"h2","properties":{},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"Limit font scaling with calc()","position":{"start":{"line":34,"column":4,"offset":3031},"end":{"line":34,"column":34,"offset":3061}}}],"position":{"start":{"line":34,"column":1,"offset":3028},"end":{"line":34,"column":34,"offset":3061}}},{"type":"text","value":"\n"},{"type":"element","tagName":"p","properties":{},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"If you would like set an exact minimum font-size in pixels you can use calc().","position":{"start":{"line":36,"column":1,"offset":3063},"end":{"line":36,"column":79,"offset":3141}}}],"position":{"start":{"line":36,"column":1,"offset":3063},"end":{"line":36,"column":79,"offset":3141}}},{"type":"text","value":"\n"},{"type":"raw","value":"<div class=\"ga